{{Buddhism}}
'''Abhirati''' "The Joyous" ({{cjkv|c=妙喜|r=Myōki|rr=Myoheui|p=Miàoxǐ}}; {{bo|w=mngon par dga' ba}}) is the eastern [[pure land]] associated with [[Akshobhya]] in [[Mahayana|Mahayana Buddhism]].{{sfn|Nattier|2000|72}} It is described in the ''Akṣobhyavyūha Sūtra'' ([[Taishō Tripiṭaka]], 313), which was first translated into Chinese by [[Lokaksema (Buddhist monk)|Lokakṣema]] by 186 CE.{{sfn|Nattier|2000|76}}

Although Abhirati emerged in the earliest era of Mahayana thought, Abhirati is far less widely known than [[Sukhavati|Sukhāvatī]], the pure land of [[Amitābha]] that has been the sole focus of [[Pure Land Buddhism]] since the [[Tang dynasty]].{{sfn|Nattier|2000|74}}

