'''Miguel Ángel Ruiz Macías''' (born August 27, 1952), better known by his pseudonym as '''Don Miguel Ruiz''', is a [[Mexican people|Mexican]] author of [[Toltec]] spiritualist and [[neoshamanism|neoshamanistic]] texts.

His work is best-received among members of the [[New Thought]] movement that focuses on ancient teachings as  a means to achieve spiritual enlightenment. Ruiz is listed as one of the Watkins 100 Most Spiritually Influential Living People in 2014.<ref>[http://www.watkinsbooks.com/review/watkins-spiritual-100-list-for-2014 Watkins’ Spiritual 100 List for 2014]</ref> Some have associated Ruiz's work with [[Carlos Castaneda]], author of ''[[The Teachings of Don Juan]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}

==Biography==
Don Miguel Ruiz was born in rural Mexico, the youngest of 13 children. 
He attended medical school, and became a surgeon. For several years he practiced medicine with his brothers.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}

A near-fatal car accident changed the direction of his life. He promptly returned to his mother to acquire greater moral understanding. He then apprenticed himself to a shaman, and eventually moved to the United States.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}

While the Toltec culture left no written records, Ruiz employs the word Toltec to signify a long tradition of indigenous beliefs in Mexico, such as the idea that a [[Nagual]] (shaman) guides an individual to personal freedom. After exploring the human mind from an indigenous as well as scientific perspective, Ruiz combines traditional wisdom with modern insights.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}

''The Four Agreements'', published in 1997; was a ''New York Times'' bestseller for more than a decade. Other books have followed: ''The Mastery of Love'', ''The Voice of Knowledge'', ''The Circle of Fire'', ''The Four Agreements Companion Book'' and ''The Fifth Agreement'', a collaboration with his son Don José. All of his books are international bestsellers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miguelruiz.com/index.php?p=donMiguel |title=don Miguel Ruiz |work=Miguelruiz.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref> His ''The Toltec Art of Life and Death'' was published in late 2015.

Fluent in Spanish and English, he often lectures and leads retreats in the United States.<ref name=YT>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nNe2oVMFqKg |title=Don Miguel Ruiz' heart Transplant Oct. 9th : An Exclusive Conversation on his New Heart |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-11-06 |accessdate=2014-04-30}}</ref> In February 2002, Ruiz suffered a near-fatal heart attack. The damage from the heart attack and subsequent coma left him with a heart functioning at only 16% of capacity and in constant pain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.miguelruiz.com/family/about-don-miguel |title=Miguel Ruiz official website, About don Miguel|accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref> He claims to have handed over an [[Eagle warrior|Eagle-Knight lineage]]<ref>[http://www.spiritofmaat.com/archive/may3/luis.htm Don José Luis interview by Julia Griffin]</ref> to his son Don José Ruiz. On October 9, 2010, Ruiz underwent a [[Heart transplantation|heart transplant]] at a hospital in Los Angeles. He was at a retreat at the Lotus Ranch in [[Wimberley, Texas]] when he was notified that a heart was available, and had chartered a plane to get back to Los Angeles.<ref name=YT/>

== The Four Agreements==
His most famous book, ''The Four Agreements'', was published in 1997 and has sold around 7.2 million copies in the U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/four-agreements-don-miguel-ruiz/1100993587?ean=2940013987647 |title=The Four Agreements: A Practical Guide to Personal Freedom [NOOK Book] |publisher=barnes and noble | accessdate=February 10, 2015}}</ref> and has been translated into 40 languages.  The book advocates personal freedom from beliefs and agreements that we have made with ourselves and others that are creating limitation and unhappiness in our lives.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/56851-the-four-agreements-gets-a-boost-from-oprah-s-super-soul-sunday.html |title=Publishers Weekly Magazine |date=April 18, 2013 |accessdate=May 6, 2014}}</ref> It was featured on the ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show|Oprah]]'' television show.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oprah.com/tows/booksseen/tows_book_20000925_dmruiz.jhtml |title=The Oprah Winfrey's Official Website |publisher=oprah.com |accessdate=October 9, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922231752/http://www.oprah.com/tows/booksseen/tows_book_20000925_dmruiz.jhtml |archivedate=September 22, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The Four Agreements are:

# Be impeccable with your word.
# Don't take anything personally.
# Don't make assumptions.
# Always do your best.

The U.S. Air Force created a "challenge coin" engraved with The Four Agreements, and Ruiz is referenced as a "National Heirloom of Mexico".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awaken.com/2014/01/don-miguel-ruiz-interview-with-women-for-one-on-toltec-wisdom-and-his-book-the-four-agreements |title=Interview with Women For One on Toltec Wisdom |accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|reason=I can find no reference for the "National Heirloom" accolade beyond Ruiz's own website and those like Awaken.com that quote it; does such an honor exist?|date=March 2016}}

He wrote a companion book to ''The Four Agreements'', titled ''The Four Agreements Companion Book'', published in 2000.

Don Miguel Ruiz's son, Don Jose Ruiz, has subsequently released a sequel with his father, ''The Fifth Agreement'', which adds a further agreement:{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}
:5. Be skeptical, but learn to listen.

