[[File:Revd Canon Evan Thomas Davies, Saint David's Church, Liverpool (Dyfrig, 1847-1927) NLW3363075.jpg|thumb|Evan Thomas Davies circa 1875<br>photographed by [[John Thomas (photographer)]])]]

'''Evan Thomas Davies''' (20 June 1847 &ndash; 31 October 1927), also known by the pseudonym "Dyfrig", was a Welsh priest. After completing his education at the school in Ystrad Meurig he moved to study at [[St David's College, Lampeter]], graduating in 1869. He then spent the next year teaching, at [[Greenock]], before, in 1870 being ordained Deacon (by [[Alfred Ollivant (bishop)|Bishop Ollivant]] of Llandaff), and, in 1871, ordained Priest. For a while he was appointed Curate of [[Llanwynno]], and later of [[Bettws, Bridgend|Betws]], [[Glamorganshire]]. In 1875, he moved to take up an appointment at St David's Welsh Church, Brownlow Hill, [[Liverpool]], before, in 1882, becoming vicar of [[Aberdovey]], and then, in 1890, of [[Pwllheli]]. In 1906 he was appointed Vicar of Llanfihangel Ysgeifiog in [[Anglesey]], where he remained until he retired in 1913. He also served as Rural Dean of [[Llyn]] (1891 to 1900), and as Residentiary Canon of [[Bangor Cathedral]] (from 1906).

His written works include ''Cydymaith y Cymro'' (1885), ''Pregethau, Erthyglau ac Areithiau'' (1894), and ''Pregethau ac Anerchiadau'' (1899). He co-edited the Welsh language religious journal ''Llusern y llan'', which ran from 1881 to 1884.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://journals.library.wales/browse/2625509/|title=Llusern y llan|website=National Library of Wales|access-date=29 June 2017}}</ref> He was a subscriber to ''Gleanings from God's Acre'' (1903), edited by [[Myrddin Fardd]], and spoke at the Church of England Congress in 1891.<ref>{{cite book|author=Church of England. Church Congress|title=The Official Report of the ... Annual Meeting of the Church Congress|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I2kQAAAAIAAJ|year=1891|publisher=Jesse W. Ward.}}</ref>

He died in [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]] in 1927, aged 80, and was buried in Glanadda cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evan Thomas Davies|url=http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-DAVI-THO-1847.html|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|last=Williams|first=Griffith John|accessdate= 2 May 2017}}</ref>

